Add small and simple event bus

This event system can be used to decouple different parts in CATMAID.
For instance, being notified about the change of the active skeleton or
active node is easily possible with the Events object. The producer (who
actually changes the active node) would trigger the event:

  Event.trigger('active-node-changed');

A Consumer, like maybe the 3D widget, that is interested in such an
event would register a callback for this event:

  Event.on('active-node-changed', callback);

A QUnit test has been added.
Namespacing: move Events into CATMAID namespace

Events: refactor to add explicit constructor and mixin functions

The behavior didn't change, but the name and the internal organization.
CATMAID.EventSource can now also be used as a constructor to create
stand-alone event sources. Additionally, using CATMAID.EventSource as a
mixin became more readable with CATMAID.asEventSource(object)---which
now all places use that use event source functionality.

Note: I suggest that we stick to this naming scheme for functions that
are intended to be used as mixins.

* E101: indentation contains mixed spaces and tabs
* E111: indentation is not a multiple of four
* E128: continuation line under-indented for visual indent
* E302: expected 2 blank lines, found 1
* W191: indentation contains tabs

Fix tests for file timestamps to drop the LLVM epoch offset.

Now that Swift is not using LLVM's TimeValue (564fc6f2 and previous commit)
there is no offset from the system_clock epoch. The offset could be added
into the tests that use touch.py (so the times would not be back in 1984)
but I decided not to do that to avoid merge conflicts in the test files.

Moved implicit resolve of package members via imports to PyImportStatement and PyFromImportStatement

Previously there was a special case in PyResolveProcessor and
PyReferenceImpl for these imports. Now they are handled in the same way
as regular PyImportedNameDefiners.

These implicit package imports and star-imports have the base class
PyImplicitImportNameDefiner.
Removed code that had become unused after removing PyResolveUtil.treeCrawlUp()

Use multi-resolve for multiple values conditionally defined in an imported module (PY-18402)

Added PyFile.multiResolveName() that is a multi-resolve version of
getElementNamed(). The same method is added to PyImportedNameDefiner,
but there is no need in extracting a super inferface at the moment.
Finally, there is the new PyImportElement.multiResolve() in addition to
resolve().

Changed some single-resolve usages to multi-resolve acorss the codebase.
There are still many less important single-resolve usages that should
be converted to multi-resolve eventually. Single-resolve variants are
deprecated now.
